<TEXT>
republican dr bob lanier will meet democrat pete 
geren in a runoff for a congressional replacement for jim wright 
the former house speaker toppled by ethics charges fort wortharea 
voters decided saturday 
lanier host of the nationally syndicated tv health show 60 
second housecall garnered 21978 ballots or 39 percent of the 
vote to 17751 votes or 32 percent for geren a fort worth 
lawyer and former aide to sen lloyd bentsen 
that made a runoff necessary since one candidate had to garner 
more than 50 percent of the vote to win 
democrat jim lane came in third with 12308 votes or 22 
percent the remaining five candidates two democrats two 
republicans and a libertarian trailed far behind the highest 
votegetter of the five was republican laraine bethke who had 
1313 votes or 24 percent 
geren immediately predicted a runoff victory pointing out that 
saturdays combined democratic vote topped the total achieved by 
republican candidates well the democrats won tonight geren 
said at a victory party in west fort worth it took us four 
candidates to do it but when you total it up we got nearly 60 
percent of the vote i call that a victory 
shortly after the results came in wright endorsed geren hes 
a good man i think he will be a good congressman said the 
former congressman who had not endorsed anyone running in the 
special election 
lane said he also would lend his support to geren 
lanier said he wasnt surprised wright had come out for geren 
and said it was a formidable endorsement but lanier predicted 
he too would win the runoff 
under state law candidates from both parties run in a single 
special election with a runoff between the two top votegetters if 
no one gets a majority the law requires the governor to schedule 
the runoff 20 to 30 days after the votes are officially counted 
which usually occurs within a week of the election 
in an emotionally charged referendum in dallas voters approved 
2to1 a proposal to reorganize the city council to equalize voting 
power between whites and minorities the proposal received 41456 
votes to 20823 against 
voters in the dallas suburb of coppell faced suspension of bus 
service at midnight sunday after voting to withdraw from the dallas 
area rapid transit authority the suburbs of carrollton irving 
plano and rowlett decided to keep the service 
at the american legion post where wright and his wife betty 
cast ballots earlier saturday a steady stream of voters turned out 
during an overcast 80degree morning 
turnout had been expected to play a large part in the election 
because few issues divided the candidates and many residents 
remained angry that they had to vote for anyone other than the 
popular wright 
in the congressional race lanier and geren had been the 
frontrunners in a recent opinion poll 
each man had his partys endorsements but lane who stressed a 
prochoice stand on abortion had endorsements from labor groups 
and wrights son wright did not endorse anyone 
also on the ballot were democrats george petrovich jr and bill 
turner republicans bethke and jim hunter and libertarian robert 
buckingham jr 
after the 1988 election the texas congressional delegation had 
20 democrats and nine republicans the democrats had a 34year lock 
on the 12th district under wright 
wright who was revered for his talents at serving constituents 
and bringing federal money and jobs to fort worth resigned his 
house seat june 30 after an ethics investigation turned up 69 
instances of alleged rules violations 
democrats went into the election controlling the house by an 
80seat margin but faced embarrassment if they lost in a district 
where registered democrats predominate 
in special elections earlier this year democrats held a seat in 
alabama and won one in indiana and republicans held a seat in 
wyoming 
in dallas the 1041 proposal called for expanding the city 
council from 11 members to 15 with 10 elected from singlemember 
districts four elected from overlapping super districts and 
the mayor elected citywide currently eight members of council are 
elected from singlemember districts and three including the 
mayor are elected at large 
proponents said the plan would give minorities a greater voice 
in city government opponents said it would dilute minority voting 
power others said the plan wouldnt substantially change the 
ethnic makeup of council districts 
the transit referendum on whether five dallas suburbs would 
withdraw from dallas area rapid transit bus service could affect 
the longrange fate of a 245 billion plan to crisscross the 
metropolitan area with 66 miles of light rail by 2010 the plan 
also called for 18 miles of rail connecting downtown to the 
dallasfort worth international airport and 37 miles of bus and car 
pool lanes for suburban commuters 
opponents said the plan would cost the suburbs a lot more than 
the bus service would be worth 
</TEXT>
