<TEXT>
lightning forced the air force early 
sunday to postpone the launch of a military navigation satellite 
for the fourth time in a week 
as rain fell on the launch pad and lightning crackled nearby 
the countdown on the delta rocket continued down to the 4minute 
mark and was held there as officials hoped for a break in the 
weather 
the launch team had only a 21minute period starting at 211 
am in which to place the navstar satellite into a desired 
11000milehigh orbit when the weather did not clear in time the 
effort was called off 
the official reason for the scrub was lightning within five 
miles of the launch pad 
the launch was rescheduled for no earlier than friday officials 
said the long delay is necessary because of other launch activity 
in the next week 
a schedule conflict with last tuesdays launch of space shuttle 
columbia and thunderstorms resulted in three earlier postponements 
the 65 million navstar satellite is to join a network of 
navigation spacecraft that can tell us and allied military forces 
where they are anywhere in the world on land sea or in the air 
and in any weather 
the satellite is the third of 21 improved navstars that the air 
force plans to orbit to complete a global system by 1992 the first 
two were launched in february and june 
