columbia to flight status the shuttles commander air force 
col brewster shaw told the crowd at ellington field it was a 
privilege to accomplish what we accomplished on this flight for the 
united states of america 
it wasnt nice it was fantastic added richards a navy 
commander and one of three space rookies on the flight 
after a 15minute ceremony the astronauts shook hands and 
hugged many of the wellwishers before climbing into vans and 
heading home with their families 
the landing ended the 30th mission of the shuttle program 
columbia for a years a hangar queen that was stripped of parts 
to keep other shuttles flying had undergone more than 250 
modifications called for after the challenger disaster 
the other crew members were navy cmdr david leestma army lt 
col james adamson and air force col mark brown 
the shuttles sonic booms startled slumbering los angeles as it 
hurtled across california minutes later shaw guided the 97ton 
orbiter to a 637 am pdt landing on a hard clay runway the 
aircraft trailing a plume of dust 
a news blackout was imposed on the mission by the air force but 
air force secretary donald rice said wednesday that a satellite was 
deployed by the astronauts during their first day in orbit on 
tuesday 
rice maintained the official silence about the satellites 
purpose but it is widely believed to be a 10ton spy satellite 
designed to take detailed photographs of military targets over a 
wide area of the globe including most of the soviet union it 
would help the united states verify soviet compliance with arms 
agreements 
the shuttle crew also reportedly monitored military sites on 
earth and was believed to have conducted experiments related to the 
star wars missile defense program 
the shuttle landed in perfect weather with unrestricted 
visibility the few people gathered to watch on rogers dry lake 
also were treated to a view of the perseid meteor shower which 
sprinkled the sky with shooting stars 
the air force base 80 miles north of los angeles has been host 
to as many as half a million people for shuttle landings but was 
closed to the public sunday because of the pentagons demand for 
secrecy 
the news media were allowed to watch and record the landing from 
about two miles 
the department of defense said secrecy was needed to limit an 
adversarys ability to determine the mission of a given dod shuttle 
flight 
